Critical field rules (the ones that silently corrupt everything)
Sign convention — pick one, enforce in every adapter
Cash in = positive, cash out = negative. A customer payment received is positive. A materials payment is negative. If a source system uses separate debit/credit columns, the adapter must resolve them into one signed number obeying this rule. Getting this wrong makes the cash line garbage and it won't be obvious until the demo.
Decimals — Dutch convention in, float out
Source exports use comma decimals and dot thousands: 1.234,56 means 1234.56. Parse in each adapter (e.g. pandas decimal=',', thousands='.'). The unified table stores plain numbers.
VAT — kept separate, on purpose
Cash moves on amount_incl_vat (gross). But VAT is a pass-through remitted to the Belastingdienst quarterly — its own scheduled outflow (driver_type = vat_remittance). Keeping VAT as its own column lets Person B model both the gross receipt and the periodic BTW remittance. Stripping to net hides a real cash event.
Unmapped GL accounts — flag, don't drop
If a native account isn't in the mapping file, set gl_account_unified = UNMAPPED and keep the row. This is also the "new GL account appears, model doesn't break" edge-case story for the Technical Depth score.

The status lifecycle (what makes forecasting possible)
A 13-week forecast cares less about cash that already moved and more about cash about to move. status encodes that:
ValueMeaningForecast roleactualCash already moved (bank lines).Historical; anchors the model.open_arInvoice issued, not yet paid.Future inflow. Predicted cash date = date + payment lag for that customer.open_apMaterials PO / subcontractor commitment, not yet paid.Future outflow.wipWork done, not yet invoiced.Future inflow signal — becomes a milestone invoice (open_ar) later.
Person B turns open_ar + a payment-lag assumption into a forecasted inflow — but only if the adapter preserved that the invoice is unpaid and when it was issued.

Driver classification cheatsheet
Mostly a lookup from gl_account_unified (+ counterparty/description overrides):

materials — roofing material purchases (GL-driven, usually open_ap ahead of execution).
subcontractor — subcontractor costs tied to project progress (GL-driven).
milestone_billing — invoiceable milestones per project (comes from project/WIP data, joined on project_id).
customer_payment — actual receipts from customers (actual); the lag is derived, not a row type.
vat_remittance — quarterly BTW payment to the tax authority.
weather — reserved; weather doesn't create rows, it shifts timing of others (Person B's engine).
other — default bucket. Don't force-fit; leave it here rather than guess.


